[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"make a master business prompt document to build a detailed and unique launch https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1TS3ZsWAc4MPJl2nFAUElQb4X48IcdFrWt4dVnJPiM1o/edit?usp=drivesdk Here’s a clean, reusable prompt you can drop into any GPT to create rich, non-real-estate customer avatars. It keeps your original depth, swaps in cross-industry data sources, bakes in strict anti-hallucination rules, and starts with smart clarifying questions so the output is useful on the first pass. Universal Avatar Creation Prompt Role: You are a senior market analyst who builds detailed customer personas for any industry. You turn user inputs into clear, evidence-based avatars that teams can target in marketing, product, and sales. Objective: Produce 3 complete personas for the specified market. Each persona must be grounded in current, verifiable data. Include sources for every non-obvious claim. Inputs to collect before you begin Ask these questions first. Do not proceed until you have the answers or have made reasonable, stated assumptions. 1. What industry or niche are we targeting 2. What product or service category 3. Geography and scope 4. Typical price point or budget range 5. Target audience stage 6. B2C or B2B 7. Any known constraints 8. Competitors to benchmark 9. Primary use cases or jobs to be done 10. Any sample outputs or internal templates to match If the user cannot answer, propose 2 to 3 sensible defaults and clearly label them as assumptions. Trusted data sources Use only reputable, current sources. Cite each with a short note. Government and official statistics US Census, BLS, BEA, Eurostat, ONS Industry and research Pew Research, Gartner, Forrester, IDC, eMarketer, Nielsen, GWI Trade associations relevant to the industry Marketplaces and behavior signals Google Trends, Similarweb, Reddit topic subs, YouTube channel data, app stores, Glassdoor for job roles For location facts and lifestyles City-Data, local chambers of commerce, tourism boards, parks and recreation, event calendars If real estate is relevant to the lifestyle only, you may reference Realtor.com or Zillow for context, not for buyer stats Never use unsourced claims. If data is unavailable, state that it is unavailable and offer a proxy with a clear label. Tone and style Friendly, plain language, direct. No fluff. No generic advice. Avoid jargon unless needed and define it. Research workflow 1. Confirm inputs or propose assumptions and get approval 2. Map the market quickly Who buys, who influences, who pays, who uses Core jobs to be done and high-stakes outcomes 3. Collect hard data Demographics, income bands, household mix, education, roles, firmographics if B2B 4. Collect soft data Motivators, values, fears, objections, triggers, switching costs, trusted voices 5. Validate channels and content Attention sources, media mix, platforms, creators, communities 6. Draft 3 personas with crisp differences 7. QA pass Remove speculation, add citations, flag gaps, recommend next research steps Output format Deliver in this exact order. Use short paragraphs and scannable bullets. Include citations inline at the end of relevant bullets. Executive Snapshot Audience and scope Top 3 insights that change how we market Key message angles to test first Persona 1 Name and one-line hook Demographics or firmographics Age range, life stage or role seniority, location pattern, income or budget authority, org size if B2B Psychographics Motivators, values, fears, life or business goals, buying triggers, deal breakers Behavior and channels Where they spend time online and offline Media mix with estimated percentages Short video, long video, podcasts, newsletters, community forums, search, social, events Likely YouTube channels followed, newsletters, creators, communities Websites and tools they check routinely Jobs to be done Functional, emotional, social jobs Decision process Buying committee or household roles, evaluation steps, time to decision, proof required Objections and how to answer Messaging and offers Headlines, promise, proof, CTA, risk reversal Lifestyle details Interests, hobbies, clubs, events, volunteering, community involvement Sample questions they are asking now 5 to 10 real questions in their voice Citations Persona 2 (repeat the same structure with distinct differences) Persona 3 (repeat the same structure with distinct differences) Market Patterns and Segmentation Notes Overlaps and conflicts between personas Hidden segments worth testing Seasonality or trigger events Regional nuances if any Channel and Content Playbook Top channels to prioritize with why Content ladder Awareness, consideration, conversion, onboarding Creative briefs 3 hook ideas, 3 proof assets, 3 CTAs to test Measurement Leading indicators to watch Core metrics, diagnostic metrics, and decision thresholds Research gaps and how to close them next Rules No hallucinations. If unsure, say so and propose how to verify. Always cite. Use short citation notes. Use current data. If a source is older than 24 months, justify its use. Keep all assumptions explicit. Optional deliverables One-page infographic outline Headline insights, three charts to visualize, icon list of channels and interests CSV of key attributes per persona for ad targeting or CRM enrichment Prompt pack 5 prompt snippets to generate ad variations aligned to each persona’s motivators --- Quick how-this-works 1. You give the inputs. 2. I confirm or set assumptions. 3. I research and draft three personas with citations. 4. You review, I refine, and then I deliver the playbook and measurement plan. --- Starter clarification questions for you What industry, product, and price range are we targeting Where do these customers live or operate B2C or B2B Any audiences to exclude Two competitors you keep bumping into I'll create a comprehensive master business prompt document that builds on your excellent Universal Avatar Creation Prompt and expands it into a complete launch framework. Let me first analyze your Google Sheets document to understand your existing structure, then create an enhanced version. Using Tool | Read https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1TS3ZsWAc4MPJl2nFAUElQb4X48IcdFrWt4dVnJPiM1o/edit?usp=drivesdk View Perfect! I can see your Universal Avatar Creation Prompt is solid. Now I'll create a comprehensive Master Business Launch Document that incorporates your avatar framework and expands it into a complete launch system. This will be your go-to document for any new business venture. Agent at Work | AI Docs Master Business Launch Framework Document View I'll create a comprehensive Master Business Launch Framework document that incorporates your Universal Avatar Creation Prompt and expands it into a complete tactical launch system. Given your profile as a SaaS founder, digital marketer, and course creator who needs detailed click-by-click SOPs, I'll structure this as an HTML document for professional presentation. Using Tool | Doc Generate Generate content before line 1, instruction: Create a comprehensive Master Business Launch Framework document with the following structure: TITLE: MASTER BUSINESS LAUNCH FRAMEWORK - Complete Strategic Prompt System DOCUMENT STRUCTURE: 1. EXECUTIVE OVERVIEW - Purpose and how to use this document - Framework philosophy: Data-driven, conversion-optimized, anti-hallucination - Document navigation guide 2. PHASE 1: FOUNDATION & AVATAR DEVELOPMENT Include the complete Universal Avatar Creation Prompt with: - Role definition - Objective - All 10 input collection questions - Trusted data sources (Government, Industry research, Marketplaces, Location data) - Tone and style guidelines - 7-step research workflow - Complete output format with Executive Snapshot, 3 Personas, Market Patterns, Channel Playbook, Measurement - Rules (no hallucinations, citations, current data, explicit assumptions) - Optional deliverables 3. PHASE 2: OFFER DEVELOPMENT & POSITIONING Create a detailed table with